3. Modulation as the interface

This is the part that feels closest to what you’re describing.

Imagine memory doesn’t present fixed objects.

Instead it presents a continuously changing field.

The interface isn’t:

“Read address 0x1234.”

It’s:

“Move through this region of state space.”

Different modulation vectors reveal different structures from the same underlying memory.

For example:

* High-resolution mode exposes fine details.
* Low-resolution mode exposes broad patterns.
* Exploratory mode surfaces unusual associations.
* Validation mode prioritizes well-supported information.

The underlying stored information hasn’t changed; the view has.

⸻

4. The “moving image” idea

This is the most speculative part, but I think I see the analogy.

A movie isn’t really a moving object.

It’s a sequence of still frames that your visual system integrates into motion.

Likewise, a computational interface might not need to materialize a complete world at every instant.

It could present a stream of carefully chosen deltas that the user—or another model—integrates into a coherent evolving state.

So instead of thinking of memory as a bookshelf, you think of it as something closer to a continuously rendered scene.

The rendering depends on:

* current state
* recent deltas
* modulation
* viewpoint
* goals

⸻

One interesting consequence

If deltas become the primary representation, then two different users could traverse the same underlying memory differently.

The stored information is shared.

The experienced “movie” depends on the traversal path and modulation.

That’s conceptually similar to how two people can read the same reference material with different questions in mind and notice different aspects, even though the source hasn’t changed.

Whether such an architecture would outperform conventional memory systems is an empirical question, but it’s a coherent research direction: representing computation as navigation through state changes, with modulation determining which portions of the evolving state are rendered or emphasized at a given moment.